tory has presented Canadian soldiers as deficient, inexperienced, and unprepared in comparison with their enemies. Questioning entrenched views, Robert Engen explores a trove of contemporaneous documents to create a remarkable new portrait of Canadians at war. Rather than the popular "band of brothers" image of soldier cohesion in battle, he finds staggering casualty rates and personnel turmoil that left Canadian infantrymen often working with and fighting beside men they hardly knew. Yet these strangers in arms continued to fight - effectively and in good spirits - against a tenacious and deadly enemy, triumphing in the face of heartrending loss and sacrifice. Challenging old narratives about the Canadian soldier and supported by cutting-edge empirical and qualitative research, Strangers in Arms crafts a new understanding of what happens at the sharp end of battle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCombat sustainability (Military science) 0aCombat sustainability (Military science). 0aCombatxPsychological aspects. 0aMilitary moralezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotivation (Psychology)zCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldierszCanadaxPsychology. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xManpowerzCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xParticipation, Canadian. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPsychological aspects. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xRegimental historieszCanada. 70(DE-601)1047575740(DE-588)4039305-7aMilitär2gnd 70(DE-601)1060754030(DE-588)4079167-1aWeltkriegg1939-19452gnd 70(DE-601)1062238440(DE-588)4040364-6aMotivation2gnd 70(DE-601)3018405630(DE-588)4556628-8aKampfeinsatz2gnd 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359908640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773599086423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773